Exploring Airbnb Listings in Columbus, OH¶

The project aims to conduct a comprehensive visualization and analysis of Airbnb listings in Columbus, Ohio, leveraging a rich dataset containing information on various aspects of these listings. With the rise of Airbnb as a popular alternative to traditional accommodations, understanding the dynamics of Airbnb listings is essential for customers. This project seeks to address key questions such as pricing trends, factors influencing listing popularity of listings, and the impact of amenities on guest satisfaction.¶

Breakdown of this notebook:¶

1. Importing Libraries.¶

2. Loading the dataset.¶

3. Data Cleaning:¶

  • Deleting redundant columns.
  • Removing duplicates.
  • Cleaning individual columns.
  • Replace the NaN values with 0 value.
  • Filling missing values with mean.
  • Some Transformations.

4. Data Visualization: Using plots to find relations between the features.¶

  • Get Correlation (Heatmap) between different variables.
  • Neighbourhood.

  • Relation between neighbourgroup and Availability of Room.
  • Map of Neighbourhood.
  • Map of Rooms Availability.
  • Price vs number of reviews.
  • Price vs number of Neighbourhood.
  • neighbourhood vs number of reviews.
  • Room type vs Availability.

5. Regression Analysis.¶

  • Linear Regression.
  • True Values vs. Predictions.

Splitting our data Train/Test¶

In [29]:
y = df['price']
x= df.drop(['price'],axis=1)
x_train,x_test,y_train,y_test=train_test_split(x,y,test_size=.1,random_state=105)

Modelling: Linear Regression¶

In [30]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.metrics import r2_score


linreg = LinearRegression()
linreg.fit(x_train,y_train)
y_pred_linreg=(linreg.predict(x_test))

print('R-squared train score: {:.3f}'.format(linreg.score(x_train, y_train)))
print('R-squared test score: {:.3f}'.format(linreg.score(x_test, y_test)))

R-squared train score: 0.044
R-squared test score: 0.061

R-squared measures the proportion of the variance in the dependent variable that is explained by the independent variables.¶

Since there is no correlation between the independent variables and the dependent variable,the model may not be able to effectively explain the variance in the dependent variable. In our cases, the R-squared value is low, it indicates a poor fit of the model to the data.¶

Plotting residuals plot (difference between predected values and actual values).¶

In [31]:
# Calculating residuals
residuals = y_test - y_pred_linreg

# Plotting the residual plot
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plt.scatter(y_pred_linreg, residuals, alpha=0.5)
plt.title('Residual Plot')
plt.xlabel('Predicted Values')
plt.ylabel('Residuals')
plt.axhline(y=0, color='r', linestyle='-')  # Adding horizontal line at y=0 as a reference
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

In the context of a residual plot:¶

  • Points above the horizontal line represent cases where the model overestimated the target variable.
  • Points below the horizontal line represent cases where the model underestimated the target variable.
